---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import TerminalBlock from "../components/TerminalBlock.astro";
import ChapterHeading from "../components/ChapterHeading.astro";
import ModesTable from "../components/ModesTable.astro";
import VaultCompare from "../components/VaultCompare.astro";

const installCmd =
  "curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/patrickmvla/bocek/main/install.sh | bash";
---

<Base title="bocek — Claude Code modes with a vault">
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden">
    <div class="hero-wash pointer-events-none absolute inset-0"></div>
    <div class="relative mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 pt-20 pb-28 sm:pt-28 sm:pb-36">
      <div class="mb-8 flex items-center gap-3">
        <span
          class="font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
          >bocek · v0</span
        >
        <span class="h-px w-12 bg-border"></span>
        <span
          class="font-heading text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-muted-foreground"
          >for claude code</span
        >
      </div>

      <h1
        class="font-heading text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-foreground sm:text-6xl sm:leading-[1.05]"
      >
        Claude Code with modes, hooks,
        <br />
        <span class="text-muted-foreground"
          >and a vault that anchors why.</span
        >
      </h1>

      <p
        class="mt-8 max-w-2xl font-sans text-lg leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
      >
        Six slash commands flip Claude between reasoning and coding. A hook
        blocks source-file writes while you're still deciding. Every resolved
        decision — with its evidence and its rejected alternatives — lands in
        <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.9em] text-foreground"
          >.bocek/vault/</code
        > and ships with your repo.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10">
        <TerminalBlock command={installCmd} title="~ — install bocek" />
      </div>

      <p
        class="mt-4 font-mono text-[11px] tracking-tight text-muted-foreground"
      >
        then <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >bocek on</code
        > in your project — adds <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >/design</code
        >, <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >/research</code
        >, <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >/implementation</code
        >, <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >/debugging</code
        >, <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >/refactoring</code
        >, <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[11px] text-foreground"
          >/review</code
        >
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- 01 — the problem -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="problem"
    number="01"
    title="A coding harness without project anchors regresses to the training-data median."
    kicker="the problem"
  >
    <div class="space-y-6 text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      <p>
        A coding harness is the software wrapping a language model — the
        orchestration loop, tools, context management, memory, guardrails.
        Claude Code is the harness around Claude. Cursor, Aider, Continue —
        each ships its own. By Anthropic's own framing, only ~1.6% of Claude
        Code's codebase is AI decision logic; the remaining ~98.4% is
        operational infrastructure. Every component encodes an assumption
        about what the model can't do on its own.
      </p>
      <p>
        What none of these harnesses ship is project-specific anchoring. With
        no recorded decisions constraining output, no project-specific
        quality bar, no mode that distinguishes reasoning from coding, the
        agent's output regresses to the median of its training corpus. You
        ask for a checkout API and you get the median checkout API — route
        handlers from training-data defaults, no inventory-locking strategy
        chosen for <em>your</em> write volume, no awareness of how Stripe
        actually handles idempotency, no record of why REST instead of GraphQL.
      </p>
      <p>
        The compounding is structural, not narrative. Each ungrounded
        generation adds median-pattern code to the project. The next
        generation reads the project, sees the median pattern, treats it as
        evidence of intent, reinforces it. The codebase converges on the
        training distribution, not on the project's actual constraints. By
        generation twenty, the agent has no way to tell which behaviors are
        deliberate and which are accidents — and neither do you.
      </p>

      <p class="text-foreground">
        Bocek is a meta-harness — additional scaffolding on top of the existing
        coding harness that encodes the project-specific layer the underlying
        harness can't reliably produce alone. Slash-command primitives that
        prescribe engineering discipline (substance, gates, ceiling protocols).
        A <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
          >PreToolUse</code
        > hook that enforces the design/code boundary at the system level.
        Stack-specific idiom files that anchor output to the actual ecosystem.
        A versioned vault that carries decisions, contracts, and discoveries
        across sessions. The model writes to the vault, not to source files,
        until you switch modes — that's a structural guarantee the underlying
        harness doesn't provide.
      </p>
    </div>
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- 02 — the shift -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="shift"
    number="02"
    title="The model is a senior systems engineer if you let it be."
    kicker="the shift"
    variant="alt"
  >
    <div class="space-y-6 text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      <p>
        An LLM is a prediction engine. Its default output is the
        <em>most common</em> pattern in training data — Stack Overflow,
        tutorials, boilerplate, unremarkable production repos. Ask for output
        and you get the median.
      </p>
      <p>
        But the same model has read every Spanner paper, every Stripe
        engineering post, every Postgres docs page, every CAP-vs-PACELC
        re-derivation, every Shopify post-mortem on flash-sale inventory
        contention. It knows ACID, isolation levels, idempotency keys,
        consensus tradeoffs, observability primitives. That knowledge sits
        below the surface — a strong default pulls it toward the average.
      </p>

      <div
        class="my-4 grid gap-px overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-border/60 sm:grid-cols-2"
      >
        <div class="bg-background p-6">
          <div class="mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
            <span class="h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full bg-muted-foreground/60"
            ></span>
            <span
              class="font-heading text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-muted-foreground"
              >executor</span
            >
          </div>
          <p
            class="font-mono text-[13px] leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
          >
            "Build me a checkout API."
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
            → the median of every checkout API in the training data
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-background p-6">
          <div class="mb-3 flex items-center gap-2">
            <span
              class="h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full bg-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
            ></span>
            <span
              class="font-heading text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
              >senior systems engineer</span
            >
          </div>
          <p class="font-mono text-[13px] leading-relaxed text-foreground">
            "What's the consistency model on the write path? Name two
            production systems doing this at our scale and one that
            doesn't and why."
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
            → ACID, CAP, named systems, named tradeoffs — engineering
            substance, not vibes
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
          >/design</code
        > primitive asks the model to clear three gates before staking a
        position: <strong class="text-foreground">idiomatic</strong> to
        <em>this</em> stack and version (React 19, Postgres 16 — not what
        docs taught five years ago); <strong class="text-foreground"
          >industry-standard</strong
        > with ≥2 named production systems (Stripe + Shopify, not "ten blog
        posts"); <strong class="text-foreground">first-class</strong> not
        workaround (platform abstractions, not a fight against them).
      </p>

      <p>
        Then the engineering: name the principles in play. <em
          >"Strong consistency on writes per ACID-I, eventual on reads —
          Postgres + read replicas, not Cassandra."</em
        > Not <em>"we'll use a database."</em>
      </p>

      <p>
        Default register is collaborative — you bring context, the model
        brings substance. Adversarial pressure is calibrated to the signal:
        confident-but-wrong gets counter-evidence, hand-waving gets
        decomposed, honest uncertainty gets helped. A tool, not the frame.
      </p>

      <p class="text-foreground">
        Stack-specific idioms (<code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
          >~/.bocek/idioms/typescript.md</code
        > and siblings) ship the production-grade default per ecosystem.
        Preflight auto-suggests the matching one.
      </p>
    </div>
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- 03 — the loop -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="loop"
    number="03"
    title="A session, start to finish."
    kicker="the loop"
  >
    <div class="space-y-6 text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      <p>
        You open Claude Code in the project and type <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.9em] text-foreground"
          >/design</code
        >.
      </p>

      <pre
        class="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-border/60 bg-card px-5 py-4 font-mono text-[13px] leading-relaxed text-foreground"><code>/design
Checkout flow. Start with the decisions I haven't made.</code></pre>

      <p>
        Design is a reasoning mode. The hook blocks source-file writes until
        you switch to a coding mode — Claude can only ask, argue, and write to
        the vault.
      </p>

      <div
        class="rounded-lg border border-border/60 bg-background-alt/40 px-5 py-4 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-foreground"
      >
        <div
          class="mb-2 font-heading text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-muted-foreground"
        >
          claude, in design mode
        </div>
        <p class="mb-2">
          You didn't say when inventory gets reserved. Three options —
        </p>
        <ul class="mb-2 space-y-0.5 pl-4 text-[14px]">
          <li>(a) at add-to-cart, 15-min expiry — Shopify's pattern.</li>
          <li>(b) at payment-start, 2-min expiry — Amazon's.</li>
          <li>(c) no lock, reconcile on conflict — low volume only.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          I'd argue for (a) at under 50 writes/sec. Under flash sales it
          starves legitimate buyers. So: what's your peak write volume, and do
          you run flash sales?
        </p>
      </div>

      <p>
        You answer. The model either records the decision or escalates and
        demands more defense. When a question resolves, it writes the
        reasoning trail to the vault:
      </p>

      <pre
        class="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-border/60 bg-card px-5 py-4 font-mono text-[12px] leading-relaxed text-foreground"><code>.bocek/vault/checkout/optimistic-locking.md

# Use optimistic locking for inventory management

## Decision
Postgres `version` column, conditional UPDATE on (id, version).
On 0 rows affected: rollback, auto-refund Stripe, return 409.

## Engineering substance applied
- Consistency: CAS via UPDATE WHERE version = $2 — no SERIALIZABLE
  required, no deadlock surface.
- Failure semantics: at-least-once Stripe + at-most-once inventory,
  reconciled via [[stripe-idempotency-research]].
- Observability: page on conflict-rate &gt; 10% sustained 5min.

## Production-grade gates
- Idiomatic — standard Postgres+Drizzle pattern.
- Industry-standard — Shopify (post-mortem, 2022), GitHub (public
  source, 2024).
- First-class — native row versioning, not a custom mutex table.

## Rejected — pessimistic (SELECT FOR UPDATE)
Wins at contention &gt; 100 + external call &lt; 50ms. Not here:
the 200-800ms Stripe call held inside a row lock collapses
throughput to 1-5/sec/product.

## Revisit when
Sustained contention &gt; 50 writers/product, or Stripe latency &gt; 1s.</code></pre>

      <p>
        When the vault holds enough decisions to ship, you type <code
          class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.9em] text-foreground"
          >/implementation</code
        >. The hook unlocks source-file writes. Implementation mode requires
        every function to open with a quote from the vault contract it
        satisfies — if a decision is missing, Claude stops and flags the gap
        instead of guessing.
      </p>

      <p class="text-foreground">
        The vault commits with your code. The next session reads it before
        writing a line.
      </p>
    </div>
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- 04 — the modes -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="modes"
    number="04"
    title="Six modes. Each demands something from you."
    kicker="the modes"
    variant="alt"
  >
    <p
      class="mb-10 max-w-2xl text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
    >
      Modes aren't features. They're contracts. The model doesn't accommodate
      weak reasoning — it escalates. You switch with a slash command; the
      contract for that mode loads, and the hook enforces what that mode can
      touch.
    </p>
    <ModesTable />
    <p
      class="mt-8 max-w-2xl text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
    >
      Modes are independent, not a pipeline. You switch whenever you need to
      — <code
        class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
        >/research</code
      > mid-design, <code
        class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
        >/debugging</code
      > mid-implementation, back to <code
        class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
        >/design</code
      > when a gap surfaces. The vault is how you carry work across the
      switches.
    </p>
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- 05 — enforcement -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="enforcement"
    number="05"
    title="Context rot is structural. Three layers of defense cover the gap."
    kicker="enforcement"
  >
    <p class="mb-10 max-w-2xl text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      Every model degrades as context grows — 95% accuracy nosediving to 60%
      past a threshold (Chroma, 18 frontier models). Position bias is baked
      into the architecture — information in the middle of context loses
      roughly 30% attention. An instruction that says "don't write code in
      design mode" does not survive a long session. So Bocek doesn't rely on
      the model remembering its own contract.
    </p>

    <div class="divide-y divide-border/60 border-y border-border/60">
      <div class="grid gap-4 py-7 sm:grid-cols-[9rem_1fr] sm:gap-10">
        <div>
          <div
            class="font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
          >
            layer 01
          </div>
          <div
            class="mt-1 font-heading text-base font-semibold text-foreground"
          >
            the hook
          </div>
        </div>
        <div
          class="space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
        >
          <p>
            A bash script registered as a <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >PreToolUse</code
            > hook. It runs outside the context window, reads <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >.bocek/mode</code
            >, and either allows or denies the tool call before it reaches
            Claude. In reasoning modes it blocks <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >Edit</code
            >, <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >Write</code
            >, and the Bash workarounds the model actually reaches for —
            <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >sed&nbsp;-i</code
            >, <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >python&nbsp;-c</code
            >, shell redirects, <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >tee</code
            >. The Bash bypass is a filed issue (<code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >claude-code#29709</code
            >) — matching Edit/Write only would be trivially defeated.
          </p>
          <p class="font-heading text-[11px] tracking-tight text-foreground">
            zero tokens · non-bypassable · can't degrade
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid gap-4 py-7 sm:grid-cols-[9rem_1fr] sm:gap-10">
        <div>
          <div
            class="font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
          >
            layer 02
          </div>
          <div
            class="mt-1 font-heading text-base font-semibold text-foreground"
          >
            the primitive
          </div>
        </div>
        <div
          class="space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
        >
          <p>
            Each mode's behavioral contract is split into a small core
            (roughly 800–2,000 tokens — Anthropic's persistence sweet spot)
            and a set of reference files loaded on demand via tool calls. The
            core lives in the highest-attention zone at the start of context.
            References arrive fresh at the end, where attention is strongest.
            The middle — where context rot bites — holds accumulated tool
            results and resolved conversation, where decay is correct.
          </p>
          <p class="font-heading text-[11px] tracking-tight text-foreground">
            in-context · degrades with length · catches what the hook can't
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid gap-4 py-7 sm:grid-cols-[9rem_1fr] sm:gap-10">
        <div>
          <div
            class="font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
          >
            layer 03
          </div>
          <div
            class="mt-1 font-heading text-base font-semibold text-foreground"
          >
            session restart
          </div>
        </div>
        <div
          class="space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
        >
          <p>
            When the session has drifted far enough that you notice, you
            restart. A fresh Claude Code window reads <code
              class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
              >.bocek/state.md</code
            > and the compiled vault and picks up at the last resolved
            decision. Not a blank slate — a continuation. Sessions are
            disposable, knowledge is permanent.
          </p>
          <p class="font-heading text-[11px] tracking-tight text-foreground">
            manual · full recovery · the vault is the memory
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p
      class="mt-10 max-w-2xl text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
    >
      Nothing registers until <code
        class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
        >bocek on</code
      >. No persona loaded, no skills attached, no always-on system prompt.
      Every token in context is a token you chose to load.
    </p>

    <div
      class="mt-12 rounded-lg border border-border/60 bg-background-alt/30 px-6 py-5"
    >
      <div
        class="mb-3 font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-muted-foreground"
      >
        what bocek does not do
      </div>
      <ul
        class="space-y-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
      >
        <li>
          <strong class="text-foreground">Validate vault entry content.</strong>
          The hook blocks file writes outside <code
            class="rounded bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
            >.bocek/</code
          >. It does not check whether a vault entry has the prescribed
          sections (engineering substance, rejected alternatives,
          production-grade gates). The human carries the quality bar.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-foreground"
            >Prevent the model from drifting in a long session.</strong
          >
          Primitive instructions decay with context. Restart on noticeable
          drift. The vault is what survives.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-foreground"
            >Guarantee any specific behavior.</strong
          >
          Bocek prescribes. The model executes those prescriptions most of
          the time, and sometimes doesn't. The system creates conditions
          for better engineering — it doesn't enforce that engineering
          happen.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-foreground">Replace human review.</strong>
          A vault that grows without an attentive human grows shallow.
          Read entries. Push back on thin ones. The discipline is yours.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </ChapterHeading>

  <!-- 06 — the vault -->
  <ChapterHeading
    id="vault"
    number="06"
    title="The code is downstream. The vault is the product."
    kicker="the vault"
    variant="alt"
  >
    <p
      class="mb-10 max-w-2xl text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
    >
      The vault is two representations of the same knowledge. The source of
      truth is Obsidian-style markdown — YAML frontmatter, wikilinks, feature
      folders — so humans can read and cross-reference it. A compiled
      per-feature layer is generated on demand by implementation mode when
      source files change. You never hand-edit the compiled layer. You commit
      the source.
    </p>

    <VaultCompare />

    <div class="mt-12 grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-3">
      <div>
        <div
          class="mb-2 font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-muted-foreground"
        >
          path convention
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
          Entries live at <code
            class="rounded bg-muted px-1 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
            >vault/&#123;feature&#125;/&#123;slug&#125;.md</code
          >. Cross-cutting in <code
            class="rounded bg-muted px-1 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
            >_shared/</code
          >. Preflight flags loose entries; <code
            class="rounded bg-muted px-1 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
            >bocek vault organize</code
          > migrates them.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div
          class="mb-2 font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-muted-foreground"
        >
          project shape
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
          <code
            class="rounded bg-muted px-1 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
            >_shared/project-shape.md</code
          > — the meta-decision (what / scale / team / constraints / non-goals
          / success). Every other decision inherits its constraints.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div
          class="mb-2 font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.22em] text-muted-foreground"
        >
          idioms
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
          <code
            class="rounded bg-muted px-1 py-0.5 font-mono text-[0.85em] text-foreground"
            >~/.bocek/idioms/&#123;stack&#125;.md</code
          > — production-grade defaults per ecosystem. Auto-suggested when
          preflight detects the stack.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p
      class="mt-10 max-w-2xl text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground"
    >
      Two formats, one direction. Compilation is lazy — only when
      implementation mode needs the feature's compiled file, only if the
      source has changed. No sync step. No stale artifacts. The vault travels
      with the code; the compiled layer is gitignored because it's a build
      artifact, regenerable from the source.
    </p>
